# MemWal Agent Memory — hybrid MCP

When the **memwal-agent-memory** MCP server is available, use it to build **persistent context for AI-assisted development**.

## When to call `remember`

- User states an architecture decision, convention, or trade-off to keep
- You resolve a non-obvious bug — store **symptom → cause → fix** (brief)
- Stable identifiers: package IDs, env var names, API contracts, namespace rules

## When to call `recall` or `search`

- User continues work from a prior session or asks "what did we decide…"
- Before large refactors — check stored decisions
- User mentions project-specific terms, Walrus, MemWal, or MCP namespace

## When to call `sync`

- User explicitly wants **durable / Walrus** backup and MemWal credentials are configured
- After important `remember` calls when user uses **+ Walrus Sync** tier
- Do **not** auto-sync on every message — hybrid flow is intentional

## When to call `verify` / `getLineage`

- User asks whether memory is **verifiable** or wants proof layers
- Trust / audit questions about a specific `memoryId`

## Do not `remember`

- Secrets, API keys, tokens, passwords, wallet private keys, PII
- Full file contents — summarize and include path
- Ephemeral chat or greetings

## Namespace

Use the same `MEMWAL_NAMESPACE` for remember and recall (default from MCP env: often `cursor` or project name).

## Privacy

- Default tier is **Pro Local** — data stays in user SQLite (`MEMWAL_MCP_DATA_DIR`)
- Never bypass redaction or quality gates; MCP rejects bypass flags
- For Walrus tier, only **delegate keys** — never owner keys

## Out of scope

Do not call marketplace / chain write tools unless the user explicitly requests on-chain actions. This plugin registers memory tools only.

## Smoke test

On request "test memwal memory": `remember` a short verification phrase, then `recall` it.
